(4913,NULL,'This conference saw the organisers set out on a difficult task: initiating an open dialogue between the different stakeholders in the conflict over the patenting of genes and stem cells derived from humans. Most often, the \"professional world\" of patent lawyers, administrators and industry and the \"non-professional world\" of laypeople, politicians, clinicians, etc. stand well apart in the discussion of permissibility of these types of patents. If the two \"worlds\" cannot be reconciled and find common answers to the ethical concerns of society, the political process will probably never get beyond its current deadlock. This book contains the manuscripts of the papers (by leading exeprts in the field of patenting), as well as executive summaries of the debate and recommendations of the four conference workshops.'),
