(5077,NULL,'Along with the economic mainstreaming of patents has come opportunistic exploitation the use of weak patent claims and flaws in the system to shakedown or extort money from businesses of all kinds. In Overcoming Patent Infringement Allegations, patent attorney Paul Hunter articulates why and how patent enforcement arrived at this critical juncture, how flaws in the system helped fuel and perpetuate patent exploitation by opportunistic entrepreneurs and, finally, suggests viable procedures and mechanisms to combat this problem. From how the patent owner makes money and what this means for the rest of us, Hunter pulls the reader through all issues related to and consequent of an encounter with an opportunist and how a company can strategize to come out on top. Informative and illustrative appendices augment a direct and informative glimpse into the extortionists operatives. This is a must-read for any executive or general counsel, running or advising a company in possession of patents of any kind.'),
(5078,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=jZhQAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','This book is part of the GLOBAL ISSUES SERIES. Each book in this series contains materials designed to facilitate the introduction of international, transnational and comparative law issues into basic law school courses. The goal of this series is to ensure that all law school graduates have sufficient familiarity with the growing impact of non-domestic sources of law, and the growing potential for transnational legal transactions and disputes, to function in an era of increasing globalization. In addition, introduction of international, transnational and comparative law materials can enhance the students\' understanding of domestic law. The philosophy behind this series may be best summarized by Justice Stephen G. Breyer\'s statement that \"This world we live in is a world where it is out of date to teach foreign law in a course called Foreign Law.\" Book jacket.'),
(5079,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=y5pQAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','This book is part of the Global Issues Series. Each book in this series contains materials designed to facilities the introduction of international, transnational and comparative law issues into basic law school courses. The goal of this series is to ensure that all law school graduates have sufficient familiarity with the growing impact of non-domestic sources of law, and the growing potential for transnational legal transactions and disputes, to function in an era of increasing globalization. In addition, introduction of international, transnational and comparative law materials can enhance the student\'s understanding of domestic law. The philosophy behind this series may be best summarized by Justice Stephen G. Breyer\'s statement that \" This world we live in is a world where we live in is a world where it is out of date to teach foreign law in a course called Foreign Law.\" Book jacket.'),
(5080,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=XaBOygAACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','The 2011 edition of this one-volume compilation of IP statutes for law students and practitioners includes all changes to statutory and regulatory law enacted during the past year. The provisions of such legislation as the Satellite Television Extension and Localism Act of 2010 and the Copyright Cleanup, Clarification, and Corrections Act of 2010, among others, are all reflected in this thoroughly up-to-date collection.'),
(5081,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=A6QXRQAACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','Perfect for an upper level seminar or course, this casebook traces the legal impacts of genetics across the legal spectrum--from family law to medical law to forensics. It addresses international and federal regulation of genetic research; medical applications including prenatal testing, pharmacogenomics, and gene therapy; paternity testing; intellectual property rights; and the use of genetic technologies by social institutions, including law enforcement, courts, insurers, employers and schools. The 3rd edition newly covers Octomom and President Obama\'s stem cell directive. No scientific background on the part of the students or professor is required.'),
(5082,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=7ACpzwEACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','IP Client Strategies in Europe provides an authoritative, insiders perspective on protecting and maximizing intellectual property for todays European clients. Featuring partners from law firms across various countries in Europe, including England, Ireland, Scotland, France, Germany, Italy, Spain, and Austria, these experts guide the reader through the complexities of the different nations IP laws and analyze noteworthy legal decisions and developments. From trademarks and patents to keyword advertising and Web content, these top lawyers discuss the critical elements of an effective pan-European IP strategy and divulge proven advice for both enforcement and litigation. They also reveal how to adapt IP tactics for individual client needs, foster sound client relationships, and avoid the common mistakes that clients and lawyers make. Additionally, these authors assess the current state of harmonization, the impact of the global economic crisis, and how to strategically use IP law in the twenty-first century. The different niches represented and the breadth of perspectives presented enable readers to get inside some of the great legal minds of today, as these experienced lawyers offer up their thoughts on the keys to success within this dynamic field.'),
